pref[i][j]=grid[i][j]+pref[i−1][j]+pref[i][j−1]−pref[i−1][j−1]

👉 This gives sum from (0,0) to (i,j)

🚀 Optimized Approach
Steps:
Create prefix sum matrix
Traverse each cell (i, j)

Check:

if pref[i][j] <= k → count++
⏱️ Complexity
Time: O(m × n)
Space: O(1) (if modify grid) or O(m × n)
🔥 Code (C++)
class Solution {
public:
    int countSubmatrices(vector<vector<int>>& grid, int k) {
        int m = grid.size(), n = grid[0].size();
        int count = 0;

        // build prefix sum in-place
        for (int i = 0; i < m; i++) {
            for (int j = 0; j < n; j++) {
                if (i > 0) grid[i][j] += grid[i-1][j];
                if (j > 0) grid[i][j] += grid[i][j-1];
                if (i > 0 && j > 0) grid[i][j] -= grid[i-1][j-1];

                if (grid[i][j] <= k) count++;
            }
        }

        return count;
    }
};
🧩 Intuition (Very Important)
Since top-left is fixed → no need to try all submatrices
Each cell represents one unique submatrix
Prefix sum converts:
O(n⁴) brute → O(n²)
❌ Common Mistakes
Forgetting - pref[i-1][j-1]
Using long long (important if sum large)
Thinking we need sliding window ❌ (not needed)
🧠 Pattern Recognition

Whenever you see:

fixed corner (like top-left)
sum constraint

👉 Think:

Prefix Sum + iterate endpoints
